
[1]shallow

   SHAL'LOW, a.

   1. Not deep; having little depth; shoal; as shallow water; a shallow
   stream; a shallow brook.

   2. Not deep; not entering far into the earth; as a shallow furrow; a
   shallow trench.

   3. Not intellectually deep; not profound; not penetrating deeply into
   abstruse subjects; superficial; as a shallow mind or understanding;
   shallow skill.

   Deep vers'd in books, and shallow in himself. Milton.

   SHAL'LOW, n. A shoal; a shelf; a flat; a sand-bank; any place where the
   water is not deep.

   A swift stream is not heard in the channel, but upon shallows of
   gravel.
